  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Mandates reporting of suspicious activities\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Expanded money laundering provisions\n- Added specific provisions related to drug-related financial crimes\n\n4. Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- Required banks to establish anti-money laundering programs\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n\n5. USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Significantly strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting and compliance requirements\n- Enhanced information sharing between financial institutions and government agencies\n\n6. Corporate Transparency Act of 2021\n- Requires certain businesses to report beneficial ownership information\n- Aims to prevent money laundering through shell companies\n\nThese statutes provide legal frameworks for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities, with substantial criminal and civil penalties for violations.",
